ial before generation. It can involve choosing additional Maven dependencies, Docker image tests, or system property configurations. I need to decide on the no_action option unless there’s solid evidence indicating more setup is required. The Ehcache-core POM has some minimal requirements like slf4j-api. I wonder if skipping the update check is part of this concrete evidence, as it could help avoid issues during tests. I want to make sure I’m enhancing reliability properly.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering native image runtime**\\n\\nI'm contemplating whether to disable the network for native image runtime. The failure seems linked to the native-image builds, possibly due to the update checker. I'm realizing that to troubleshoot effectively, I might need the last log, but it’s truncated and not showing much. According to Ehcache documentation, the update checker is on by default and can be disabled with a system property. I think generated tests need this configuration. Also, I should note that an extra dependency is necessary for testing transaction classes.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Hibernate Dependencies**\\n\\nI'm thinking about the agent exploring the Hibernate package. I wonder if it will need hibernate-core since normal library usage might include optional integrations, not just core functionalities. It feels like we shouldn't add broad optional dependencies unless absolutely necessary. The existing build excludes Hibernate, even though there seems to be coverage with BeanUtils in hibernate.management.impl. But it raises the question of how to compile since that class doesn’t import Hibernate. Other classes would need it, but tests don’t cover this.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating JMS and BTM**\\n\\nI'm looking into the existing build which includes `org.apache.geronimo.specs:geronimo-jms_1.1_spec:1.1.1` and BTM. I wonder why JMS is involved here. It’s possible that BTM relies on JMS interfaces, but maybe they aren’t transitive? I also notice that `DefaultTransactionManagerLookup` has factories specifically for Bitronix. It seems important to inspect the imports further to clarify how everything connects. That should help in understanding the dependencies better!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_cpz8iiXcvLKd8CGMFjHD84Ga|fc_051837fa0b267e4c016a4309a887948196bb0dab2b903ba472", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/net.sf.ehcache/ehcache-core/2.4.4/src/test/java/net_sf_ehcache/ehcache_core/DefaultTransactionManagerLookupTest.java"}}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_IkX1kH8wXd7an5qUyeRoeDqz|fc_051837fa0b267e4c016a4309a887a481968629fb5417fe1177", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/net.sf.ehcache/ehcache-core/2.4.4/src/test/java/net_sf_ehcache/ehcache_core/CacheTransactionHelperTest.java"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 7272, "output": 1221, "cacheRead": 32256, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 40749, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1782778260056, "responseId": "resp_051837fa0b267e4c016a430994e120819683ec2da4b69e68a4"}}
